</div>Possible family tree of [[dinosaur]]s, [[bird]]s and [[mammal]]s<ref name="BentonDonoghue2007DateTreeOfLife" /><ref name="Benton1999PhylogenyOfMajorTetrapodGroups" /></div>
Amniotes, whose eggs can survive in dry environments, probably evolved in the Late Carboniferous period ({{ma|330|Permian|Ma}}). The earliest fossils of the two surviving amniote groups, [[synapsid]]s and [[sauropsid]]s, date from around {{ma|313|Ma|Carboniferous}}.<ref name="BentonDonoghue2007DateTreeOfLife">{{cite journal |last1=Benton |first1=Michael J. |authorlink1=Michael Benton |last2=Donoghue |first2=Philip C. J. |date=January 2007 |title=Paleontological Evidence to Date the Tree of Life |url=http://mbe.oxfordjournals.org/content/24/1/26.full |journal=Molecular Biology and Evolution |volume=24 |issue=1 |pages=26‚Äì53 |doi=10.1093/molbev/msl150 |pmid=17047029 |accessdate=2015-02-12 |ref=harv}}</ref><ref name="Benton1999PhylogenyOfMajorTetrapodGroups">{{cite journal |last=Benton |first=Michael J. |date=May 1990 |title=Phylogeny of the Major Tetrapod Groups: Morphological Data and Divergence Dates |journal=[[Journal of Molecular Evolution]] |volume=30 |issue=5 |pages=409‚Äì424 |doi=10.1007/BF02101113 |pmid=2111854 |ref=harv|bibcode=1990JMolE..30..409B }}</ref> The synapsid [[pelycosaur]]s and their descendants the [[therapsid]]s are the most common land vertebrates in the best-known Permian ({{ma|Permian|Triassic|Ma}}) fossil beds. However, at the time these were all in [[temperate]] zones at middle [[latitude]]s, and there is evidence that hotter, drier environments nearer the Equator were dominated by sauropsids and amphibians.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Sidor |first1=Christian A. |authorlink1=Christian Sidor |last2=O'Keefe |first2=F. Robin |last3=Damiani |first3=Ross |last4=Steyer |first4=J. S√©bastien |last5=Smith |first5=Roger M. H. |last6=Larsson |first6=Hans C. E. |last7=Sereno |first7=Paul C. |authorlink7=Paul Sereno |last8=Ide |first8=Oumarou |last9=Maga |first9=Abdoulaye |date=April 14, 2005 |title=Permian tetrapods from the Sahara show climate-controlled endemism in Pangaea |url=http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v434/n7035/full/nature03393.html |journal=Nature |volume=434 |issue=7035 |pages=886‚Äì889 |bibcode=2005Natur.434..886S|doi=10.1038/nature03393 |pmid=15829962 |accessdate=2008-09-08 |display-authors=3 |ref=harv}}</ref>

The [[Permian‚ÄìTriassic extinction event]] wiped out almost all land vertebrates,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Smith |first1=Roger |last2=Botha |first2=Jennifer |date=September‚ÄìOctober 2005 |title=The recovery of terrestrial vertebrate diversity in the South African Karoo Basin after the end-Permian extinction |url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1631068305000849 |journal=[[Comptes rendus de l'Acad√©mie des sciences|Comptes Rendus Palevol]] |volume=4 |issue=6‚Äì7 |pages=623‚Äì636 |doi=10.1016/j.crpv.2005.07.005 |accessdate=2015-02-13 |ref=harv}}</ref> as well as the great majority of other life.<ref>{{harvnb|Benton|2005}}</ref> During the slow recovery from this catastrophe, estimated to have taken 30 million years,<ref name="SahneyBenton2008RecoveryFromProfoundExtinction">{{cite journal |last1=Sahney |first1=Sarda |last2=Benton |first2=Michael J. |date=April 7, 2008 |title=Recovery from the most profound mass extinction of all time |url=http://rspb.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/royprsb/275/1636/759.full.pdf |format=PDF |journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society B |volume=275 |pages=759‚Äì765 |issue=1636 |doi=10.1098/rspb.2007.1370 |pmc=2596898 |pmid=18198148 |accessdate=2015-02-13 |ref=harv}}</ref> a previously obscure sauropsid group became the most abundant and diverse terrestrial vertebrates: a few fossils of [[archosauriformes]] ("ruling lizard forms") have been found in Late Permian rocks,<ref>{{harvnb|Gauthier|Cannatella|de Queiroz|Kluge|1989|p=[https://repository.si.edu/bitstream/handle/10088/4689/VZ_1989GauthieretalHierLife.pdf 345]}}</ref> but, by the [[Middle Triassic]], archosaurs were the dominant land vertebrates. Dinosaurs distinguished themselves from other archosaurs in the Late Triassic, and became the dominant land vertebrates of the Jurassic and Cretaceous periods ({{ma|Jurassic|Paleogene|Ma}}).<ref>{{cite journal |last=Benton |first=Michael J. |date=March 1983 |title=Dinosaur Success in the Triassic: A Noncompetitive Ecological Model |url=http://palaeo.gly.bris.ac.uk/Benton/reprints/1983success.pdf |format=PDF |journal=[[The Quarterly Review of Biology]]  |volume=58 |issue=1 |pages=29‚Äì55 |jstor=2828101 |accessdate=2008-09-08 |doi=10.1086/413056}}</ref>

During the Late Jurassic, birds evolved from small, predatory [[theropod]] dinosaurs.<ref name="padian2004">{{harvnb|Padian|2004|pp=210‚Äì231}}</ref> The first birds inherited teeth and long, bony tails from their dinosaur ancestors,<ref name="padian2004" /> but some had developed horny, toothless [[beak]]s by the very Late Jurassic<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Lian-hai  Hou |author2=Zhonghe Zhou |authorlink2=Zhou Zhonghe |last3=Martin |first3=Larry D. |authorlink3=Larry Martin |last4=Feduccia |first4=Alan |authorlink4=Alan Feduccia |date=October 19, 2002 |title=A beaked bird from the Jurassic of China |url=http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v377/n6550/abs/377616a0.html |journal=Nature |volume=377 |pages=616‚Äì618 |issue=6550 |bibcode=1995Natur.377..616H |doi=10.1038/377616a0 |accessdate=2008-09-08 |ref=harv}}</ref> and short [[pygostyle]] tails by the [[Early Cretaceous]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Clarke |first1=Julia A. |author2=Zhonghe Zhou |author3=Fucheng Zhang |date=March 2006 |title=Insight into the evolution of avian flight from a new clade of Early Cretaceous ornithurines from China and the morphology of ''Yixianornis grabaui''|journal=[[Journal of Anatomy]] |volume=208 |issue=3 |pages=287‚Äì308 |doi=10.1111/j.1469-7580.2006.00534.x |pmc=2100246 |pmid=16533313 |ref=harv}}</ref>

