{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}} {{Infobox person | name = Hamida Khuhro | birth_date = {{birth date|1936|8|13|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Larkana]], Pakistan | death_date = {{death date and age|2017|2|12|1936|8|13|df=y}} | death_place = [[Karachi]], Pakistan | nationality = Pakistani | alma_mater = [[SOAS, University of London]] | relatives = [[Muhammad Ayub Khuhro]] (father) }}
'''Hamida Khuhro''' (13 August 1936 ‚Äì 12 February 2017)<ref name="obit">{{cite news|title=Transitions: Hamida Khuhro, noted historian, passes away|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1324958/transitions-hamida-khuhro-noted-historian-passes-away/|accessdate=16 February 2017|work=The Express Tribune|date=13 February 2017}}</ref> was a [[Pakistan]]i politician and historian who twice served as [[Sindh|Sindh's]] Minister for Education and also served as a Professor of History at the [[University of Sindh]].<ref name="Khuhro">{{Cite news|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1324389/former-sindh-education-minister-dr-hamida-khuhro-dies/|title=Former Sindh education minister Dr Hamida Khuhro dies - The Express Tribune|date=2017-02-12|newspaper=The Express Tribune|access-date=2017-02-12|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/185790-Former-education-minister-Hamida-Khuhro-passes-away|title=Former education minister Hamida Khuhro passes away|website=www.thenews.com.pk|language=en|access-date=2017-02-12}}</ref>
==Family and education== Khuhro is the daughter of [[Muhammad Ayub Khuhro]], a former Chief Minister of Sindh.<ref name="PAS" /> She has a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] in South Asian History from the [[University of London]]<ref name="worldsindhi1">{{cite web |url=http://www.worldsindhi.org/pastevents/biographies/hamidakhuhro.html |title=Conference 2003 |publisher=World Sindhi Institute |accessdate=21 November 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312134332/http://www.worldsindhi.org/pastevents/biographies/hamidakhuhro.html |archivedate=12 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and also attended the Universities of [[University of Karachi|Karachi]], [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]] and [[University of Oxford|Oxford]].<ref name="oup"/> She is a [[Muslim]] and is married.<ref name="PAS">{{cite web|url=http://www.pas.gov.pk/index.php/members/profile/en/9/25 |title=Provincial Assembly of Sindh: Member Profile |publisher=Provincial Assembly of Sindh |accessdate=21 November 2013}}</ref>
==Career== ===Academia=== As an academic historian, Khuhro taught at Karachi and Oxford universities before becoming a professor at [[Sindh University]].<ref name="oup"/>
===Political=== Khuhro left Sindh University to concentrate on politics and writing. She joined the [[Sindh National Alliance]] in 1987 and in 1993 became a member of the [[Pakistan Muslim League]]. She had been appointed as Sindh's Minister for Education and Literacy in 1990.<ref name="worldsindhi1"/><ref name="oup">{{cite web|url=http://www.oup.com/us/catalog/general/subject/HistoryWorld/Pakistan/?view=usa&ci=9780195475197 |title=Karachi: Megacity of Our Times |publisher=Oxford University Press |date=16 May 2010 |accessdate=21 November 2013}}</ref>
In 2004, Khuhro was again appointed as Minister for Education.{{citation needed|date=November 2013}}
== Death == Khuhro died in [[Karachi]] after a brief illness on 12 February 2017, aged 80.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/130807-Hamida-Khuhro-passes-away-in-Karachi|title=Hamida Khuhro passes away in Karachi|last=|first=|date=12 February 2017|website=Geo.tv|language=en-US|access-date=2017-02-12}}</ref><ref name="Khuhro" />
